Today we bought for the first time TPU filament (95A), and we want to use it to make star wheels.
We have seen some teams use TPU for their wheels like 5951 in their end effector, but have not seen any team use it for star wheels, so we would like to know if anyone did it and if it actually worked the same way a star wheel would.

IMG-20250624-WA0070892√ó795 61.2 KB

We printed round wheels instead of star ones, but there‚Äôs no reason you can‚Äôt.

IMG_12781920√ó1440 381 KB

Things I‚Äôd say:

  1. Expect to play with slicer settings. Wall count will drastically change how it behaves, as will flow rates. Changing your filament supplier can also change things. In my experience, getting a TPU print the way you want it is equal parts art and science in a way that you don‚Äôt see with PLA/PETG/other-rigid-filament prints.
  2. I‚Äôd consider printing a rigid hub with more of a spline, so you have a more reliable way to transmit torque from the hex shaft. Alternatively, plan to play with the size of the hex and wall count right in there to get a good fit.

You absolutely can, however our team found that printing the AM or WCP star wheels with 95 TPU was way too stiff for something like coral intaking or indexing this year. We ended up buying 30/40/60a star wheels from AM instead for our prototyping and final products (which unfortunately ended up costing nearly $1000 in consumable parts‚Ä¶)

There‚Äôs a posibility you could modify the CAD to have thinner spokes or something similar to try to ‚Äòsoften‚Äô the star spokes by adding flexibility while still using the harder durometer filament

We did for our ground intake this year. Although they are not very good at gripping onto things, they are very good at surviving getting hit by coral, and they worked well for us as a system to push the coral more toward the middle of our intake.

IMG_57741920√ó2560 653 KB

The black ones were printed with 95A TPU from Overture, the blue ones are from Andymark

We haven‚Äôt had an excuse to print star wheels, but we‚Äôve printed a lot of intake wheels out of TPU.

FRC1153_AlgaeWheels21920√ó1440 164 KB

FRC1153_AlgaeWheels_20251920√ó1440 224 KB

One simple way to increase the grip of TPU wheels is to change the ‚ÄúFuzzy Skin‚Äù setting in your slicer software. This adds random permutations to the surface of the print, which makes TPU a lot more grippy.

FuzzySkin830√ó1322 109 KB

FuzzySkin2726√ó188 23.8 KB

We also experiment a lot with different infill patterns, wall thicknesses, and sometimes print without top/bottom layers to increase compliance.

FRC1153_CoralRoller_20251920√ó1440 164 KB
